passages.text: Australia | Transport & Logistics Qantas
Equity Research August 27, 2025

The FY25 UPBT is a strong result, slightly ahead of market expectations, and a little below our expectations. The Board has declared another dividend of 26.4cps (base 16.5cps, special 9.9cps). Qantas are seeing strong RASK and capacity environment into 1H26 ahead of expectations by \(\sim 3\%\) , however these would be partially offset by higher fuel and operating costs of \(\sim\) \(\)200\mathrm{mn}\$ .

FY25 results: Qantas reported underlying PBT of \(\) 2,394\mathrm{mn}\$ which is slightly below us by \(2.3\%\) (forecast \(\) 2,451\mathrm{mn}\$ ), but marginally ahead of consensus \((+0.4\%)\) . Net debt came in at \(\) 5bn\(target range is\) \ \(4.6bn -\) 5.7bn). Capex came in at \(\) 3.9\(\) (guidance \(\) 3.8bn\(to\) \ \(3.9bn\) ).

Capital management: The Board has announced a final dividend of 16.5cps, as well as a special dividend of 9.9cps, both franked. This total of 26.4cps compares to our forecast of 27.5cps (final 16.5cps, special 11cps).

Guidance: With strong demand expected to continue across the flying businesses in 1H26, management are expecting Group Domestic RASK to be up \(3 - 5\%\) , while also expecting capacity growth of \(\sim 5\%\) . The outlook for Group International RASK is to expected be up by \(2 - 3\%\) as capacity is also expected to increase by \(\sim 3\%\) .
Loyalty EBIT in FY26 is expected to grow \(10 - 12\%\) in FY26
1H26 fuel cost is expected to be \(\) 2.6bn\(VA consensus\) \ \(2.5bn\) .
FY26 D&A and net finance cost is expected to be \(\sim\) 2.3bn and \(\) 0.3bn\(, which is in - line with VA consensus expectations.
Capex guidance for FY26 is unchanged to be between \(\) 4.1bn\(and\) \ \(4.3bn\) .
New aircraft delivery expected to be 20 in FY26 (as compared previous guidance for the of 21 aircrafts), and then 29 in FY27.
Conference call details: Management will be hosting a conference call at 11:00am AEST. Register here https://s1.c- conf.com/diamondpass/10048866- judzp3. html

- Qantas Domestic EBIT came in at \(\) 409\mathrm{mn}\((-3.1\%\$ on the pcp).- Qantas International EBIT came in at\)\\(293\mathrm{mn}\) \((+15\%\) on the pcp).- Jetstar delivered EBIT of \(\) 330\mathrm{mn}\(up by\) 91.9\%\$ on the pcp which is a record.- Qantas Loyalty EBIT came in at \(\) 301\mathrm{mn}\$ which is up by \(24.9\%\) on the pcp.

Overall: While the 2H25 results were largely in line with expectations, the outlook remains strong. Travel demand is expected to remain strong through 1H26, supporting higher capacity growth than expected, and strong RASK growth. There are some offsets with higher industry costs (airport charges, same- job- same- pay) and additional costs for the introduction of new fleets. While there are earnings benefits from the new aircraft deliveries, Qantas is incurring \(\) 160\mathrm{mn}\$ of costs in FY26 ( \(\) 130\mathrm{mn}\$ in FY25), highlighting the underlying strength of the FY25 result. Trading on a current 12mth forward PE of \(9.1x\) , we continue to see the significant discount to the market as too wide. Following the strong 2H25 result and 1H26 outlook, we continue to see upside to fair value for Qantas.

Qantas is an Australian airline which operates under a dual- brand strategy of Qantas (mainline) and Jetstar (LCC). It operates both the brands in domestic and international markets. The Company also has a Qantas Loyalty business, which is the second most profitable division of the Group behind domestic operations.

Our valuation for Qantas is based using a mid- point between the current PE discount to the market and the historical discount of \(33\%\) while the business was paying dividends. The use of mid- point to PE discount multiples is on the basis that Qantas are expected to resume dividends in February 25. We see underlying competitive structure of the aviation industry in the Australian market remaining intact, leading to a period of stable earnings post COVID- 19.

Risks: The main risks facing Qantas which may impede the share price reaching our price target include: another aggressive price war with new owners of Virgin Australia domestically, a slowdown in demand for travel unmatched by capacity adjustments; International borders remaining closed for longer than expected; an air accident, or prolonged issue with one of the key fleet types used by the Group; a spike in the AUD cost of oil which is not recoverable from passengers. Conversely, lower AUD oil prices, a stronger recovery from COVID- 19 or a further easing of the competitive on key international routes gives upside to our price target.

Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period.

Jefferies Franchise Picks include stock selections from among the best stock ideas from our equity analysts over a 12 month period. Stock selection is based on fundamental analysis and may take into account other factors such as analyst conviction, differentiated analysis, a favorable risk/reward ratio and investment themes that Jefferies analysts are recommending. Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss. Stocks having 120 day volatility in the bottom quartile of S&P stocks will continue to have a 15% stop loss, and the remainder will have a 20% stop. Franchise Picks are not intended to represent a recommended portfolio of stocks and is not sector based, but we may note where we believe a Pick falls within an investment style such as growth or value.
